<font color="#FF0000">RE RHETORIC</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 28 18:00:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
What I find offensive is your passing judgment on the lawmakers of this country. Where do you get off calling people vile names? <br><br>
Do you mean that passing this amendment makes the proponents &quot;criminals&quot;? <br><br>
On one hand, you say that our government's involvement in Vietnam was &quot;criminal&quot;, and on the other hand, you refer to those who fled the country as being &quot;cowards&quot;. You mean that those who refused to take part in what you term, &quot;criminal acts&quot; were wrong? <br><br>
Do you honestly think that what you term, &quot;deifying&quot; the flag, will actually &quot;mute criticism&quot; of the government? Why don't you turn on Limbaugh some afternoon?<br><br>
I would much rather listen to someone who is patriotic, than one who passes judgment in a slanderous and intimidating manner.<br><br>
I would be the first to admit that our form of government and the people who administer it are far from perfect. But, I also feel that those whom you refer to as &quot;criminal&quot; or &quot;do nothings&quot; are capable of leading.<br><br>
I encourage you to reread your vitriolic messages to this website, then ask yourself what/who your words remind you of.<br><br>
You are against an Amendment that protects the flag from desecration. I have no problem with that. Leave your inflammatory rhetoric at home. I DO have a big problem with that.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


